                            <comment id="12905963" author="gagravarr" created="Fri, 3 Sep 2010 18:02:48 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Support added in r992368 and r992375.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All of these are now handled as strongly typed properties, based on their xmp types and keys&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12907391" author="solsson" created="Wed, 8 Sep 2010 21:03:21 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;A question on the implementation:&lt;br/&gt;
Should Tika really have a fallback to string on fields with expected non-string types. For example&lt;br/&gt;
               Object length = directory.getObject(ExifDirectory.TAG_ORIENTATION);&lt;br/&gt;
               if(length instanceof Integer) &lt;/p&gt;
{
                  metadata.set(Metadata.ORIENTATION, Integer.toString( ((Integer)length).intValue() ));
               }
&lt;p&gt; else &lt;/p&gt;
{
                  metadata.set(Metadata.ORIENTATION, directory.getString(ExifDirectory.TAG_ORIENTATION));
               }
&lt;p&gt;Isn&apos;t there a risk that this produces type errors for the application that uses Tika? I think it would be better if the value is skipped when it can&apos;t be parsed to the expected type.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12907561" author="solsson" created="Thu, 9 Sep 2010 09:41:41 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;An alternative would be to have a secondary field with same name but &quot;_str&quot; appended or something.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
